The paper discusses the creation of Digital Ecosystems, which involves the use of self-organizing properties of biological ecosystems to evolve high-level software applications. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category, which deals with the study of systems composed of multiple interacting intelligent agents. 

The paper also mentions the use of evolutionary computing to find solutions to satisfy locally relevant constraints, which could place it in the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category, which deals with the design, development, and maintenance of software systems. 

The Digital Ecosystem is described as a decentralised peer-to-peer network, which could place the paper in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms and systems for distributed computing. 

The paper also mentions the use of measures originating from theoretical ecology to evaluate the Digital Ecosystem, which could place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category, which deals with the study of social and information networks. 

Finally, the paper discusses the likeness of the Digital Ecosystem to biological ecosystems, which could place it in the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category, which deals with the study of neural networks and evolutionary algorithms.
